u003Cp\u003EAt week 12 of development, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver\u003C/strong\u003E is still the primary site of haematopoiesis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring embryonic and fetal development, haematopoiesis occurs at different sites:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eyolk sac\u003C/strong\u003E is the first site of blood cell formation, beginning in week three.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eliver\u003C/strong\u003E becomes the main site from week six until week 24\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E takes over as the primary site from week 24 onwards\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Espleen\u003C/strong\u003E contributes minimally to haematopoiesis during fetal development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethymus\u003C/strong\u003E is specifically involved in T lymphocyte development but is not a primary site of haematopoiesis\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haematopoietic stem cells first develop in the yolk sac during week three of embryonic development","The liver is the primary site of haematopoiesis from weeks 6-24 of gestation","Bone marrow becomes the primary site of haematopoiesis from 24 weeks gestation onwards"],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48734"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15945"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48734"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T12:52:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T12:52:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8636"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"q